Horace at the time of their migration, Ι think, could hardly be less than twelve years old. That age will agree well enough with the term, mihi parvo, which chronicles the stripes of Orbilius (2 E. 1. 70.); and an earlier date, Ι fear, will hardly allow sufficient age for many points of observ- ation on life and manners, picked up by the boy Horace be- fore quitting the neighbourhood of Venusia. I speak ad- visedly, when I say, that there appears no proof or vestige of his ever having lived in that country again: a hasty visit, perhaps, in some year soon after the battle of Philippi, to settle old accounts, and to see once more the friends of his youth, seems the only feasible supposition which his own history of his life and writings will possibly admit.
